</p><p>The consequence of this difference is that at every step, a system o=
f algebraic equations has to be solved. This increases the computational co=
st considerably. If a method with <i>s</i> stages is used to solve a differ=
ential equation with <i>m</i> components, then the system of algebraic equa=
tions has <i>ms</i> components. This can be contrasted with implicit <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_multistep_method" title=3D"Linear=
 multistep method">linear multistep methods</a> (the other big family of me=
thods for ODEs): an implicit <i>s</i>-step linear multistep method needs to=
 solve a system of algebraic equations with only <i>m</i> components, so th=
e size of the system does not increase as the number of steps increases.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-S=C3=BCli_2003_353_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods#cite_note-S%C3%BCli=
_2003_353-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
