Kutta methods, but not all implicit Runge=E2=80=93Kutta methods are colloca=
tion methods.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods#cite_note-30"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss%E2%80%93Legendre_=
method" title=3D"Gauss=E2=80=93Legendre method">Gauss=E2=80=93Legendre meth=
ods</a> form a family of collocation methods based on <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss_quadrature" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gauss =
quadrature">Gauss quadrature</a>. A Gauss=E2=80=93Legendre method with <i>s=
</i> stages has order 2<i>s</i> (thus, methods with arbitrarily high order =
can be constructed).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods#cite_note-31"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The method with two stages (and thus order four) has Butcher table=
au:
</p>
