pedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></=
dl>
<p>where <i>e</i> stands for the vector of ones. The function <i>r</i> is c=
alled the <i>stability function</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods#c=
ite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> It follows from the formula that <i>r</i> is the q=
uotient of two polynomials of degree <i>s</i> if the method has <i>s</i> st=
ages. Explicit methods have a strictly lower triangular matrix <i>A</i>, wh=
ich implies that det(<i>I</i> =E2=88=92 <i>zA</i>) =3D 1 and that the stabi=
lity function is a polynomial.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Iserles_1996_60_34-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kut=
ta_methods#cite_note-Iserles_1996_60-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The numerical solution to the linear test equation decays to zero if=
 | <i>r</i>(<i>z</i>) | &lt; 1 with <i>z</i> =3D <i>h</i>=CE=BB. The set of=
 such <i>z</i> is called the <i>domain of absolute stability</i>. In partic=
ular, the method is said to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sti=
ff_equation#A-stability" title=3D"Stiff equation">absolute stable</a> if al=
l <i>z</i> with Re(<i>z</i>) &lt; 0 are in the domain of absolute stability=
. The stability function of an explicit Runge=E2=80=93Kutta method is a pol=
ynomial, so explicit Runge=E2=80=93Kutta methods can never be A-stable.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Iserles_1996_60_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runge%E2%80%93Kutta_methods#cite_note-Iserles_1996_=
60-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If the method has order <i>p</i>, then the stability function satisf=
ies <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D=
"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><mat=
h xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle r(=
